💻 How to Run QuickBite (Flask Web App) Locally on Your Laptop

Below are the step-by-step instructions for running your QuickBite online food ordering system from GitHub using Visual Studio Code (VS Code).

🧩 1️⃣ Clone the Repository

Open VS Code

Go to View → Terminal

In the terminal, run this command to clone your GitHub repo:

git clone https://github.com/<your-username>/<your-repository-name>.git


(Replace with your actual GitHub repo link — for example:)

git clone https://github.com/danishmuzzafar/quickbite.git


Navigate into the project folder:

cd quickbite

🐍 2️⃣ Check Python Installation

You need Python 3.10 or higher.
To check:

python --version


If it doesn’t show a version, download and install Python from:
🔗 https://www.python.org/downloads/

⚙️ 3️⃣ Create a Virtual Environment (venv)

Inside the project folder, create an isolated environment so dependencies don’t conflict with your global setup.

Run:

python -m venv venv


Then activate it:

On Windows (PowerShell):

venv\Scripts\activate


On Mac/Linux:

source venv/bin/activate


You’ll know it’s activated because your terminal will show:

(venv)

📦 4️⃣ Install Dependencies

Now install all required Python packages from requirements.txt:

pip install -r requirements.txt


This will install:

Flask

SQLAlchemy

Flask-SQLAlchemy

Flask-Migrate

Gunicorn (for deployment)

and other necessary libraries

🗃️ 5️⃣ Initialize the Database

The app uses SQLite as the database.

If your repo already includes instance/database.db, you’re good — skip this step.

Otherwise, run these commands in the Python shell inside VS Code:

python


Then:

from app import app, db
with app.app_context():
    db.create_all()
exit()


✅ This creates a new SQLite database file at:

instance/database.db

🍔 6️⃣ Run the Flask Server

Start the development server using:

python app.py


If your app.py has this line:

if __name__ == "__main__":
    app.run(debug=True)


Then it will launch automatically.

✅ After starting, you’ll see output like:

 * Running on http://127.0.0.1:5000


Copy and open that URL in your browser.

🌐 7️⃣ Explore the Website

You can now use QuickBite locally:

Page	URL	Description
🏠 Home	http://127.0.0.1:5000/	Hero banner + intro
🍕 Menu	/menu	All food items (dynamic from DB)
🛒 Cart	/cart	Add, view, and checkout
👤 Checkout	/login_checkout	Guest / register / admin login
👑 Admin Dashboard	/admin_dashboard	Orders, users, charts, add items
🔑 8️⃣ Admin Login (Default Credentials)

If the database has the default admin from setup, use:

Email: danish@gmail.com
Password: admin


Otherwise, you can manually insert one in DB or via script:

from app import app, db
from models import User

with app.app_context():
    admin = User(first_name="Danish", last_name="Muzzafar",
                 email="danish@gmail.com", phone="12123456789",
                 address="Birmingham", password="admin", type="admin")
    db.session.add(admin)
    db.session.commit()

🖼️ 9️⃣ Folder Explanation (for Developers)
Folder/File	Purpose
app.py	Main Flask app file (all routes)
models.py	Database models for User, Food, Order, etc.
static/	CSS, JS, and images
templates/	HTML templates for each page
instance/database.db	SQLite database file
requirements.txt	Project dependencies
🧰 10️⃣ Common Issues & Fixes
Issue	Cause	Fix
ModuleNotFoundError: No module named 'flask'	Flask not installed	pip install flask
sqlite3.OperationalError: no such table	DB not created	Run db.create_all() inside app context
Page not loading images	Wrong static path	Ensure /static/... paths are correct
Port already in use	Flask already running	Stop with Ctrl + C and rerun
🚀 11️⃣ Optional: Run via VS Code Debug

In VS Code:

Go to Run → Add Configuration

Choose Flask

Set "app.py" as your entry file

Click ▶️ Run — Flask server will start automatically in debug mode

🔒 12️⃣ Stop the Server

When done, stop it with:

Ctrl + C


To deactivate the virtual environment:

deactivate

✅ Summary of Commands
# 1. Clone repo
git clone https://github.com/yourname/quickbite.git
cd quickbite

# 2. Create venv
python -m venv venv
venv\Scripts\activate  # (Windows)
# or
source venv/bin/activate  # (Mac/Linux)

# 3. Install dependencies
pip install -r requirements.txt

# 4. Create DB (if not exists)
python
>>> from app import app, db
>>> with app.app_context(): db.create_all()
>>> exit()

# 5. Run Flask app
python app.py

🧡 That’s it!

Your QuickBite Online Food Ordering System will now run on your local machine.
You can modify templates, add new foods, or test orders right from VS Code.
